Japan, Australia Stock Futures Gain on U.S. Consumer Confidence

-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a   a n d   S a t o s h i   K a w a n o
-- 
2011-04-17T23:16:33Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-17/japan-australia-stock-futures-advance-on-u-s-data-woodside-rises-on-oil.html
Japanese and Australian  stock
futures  gained as better-than-forecast U.S. consumer confidence
and manufacturing data bolstered optimism in the global economy.  American depositary receipts of Mizuho Financial Group
Inc., Japan’s No. 3 publicly traded lender, advanced 1.2 percent
from the closing share price on April 15 in  Tokyo . Those of Sony
Corp., Japan’s largest exporter of consumer electronics, rose
0.3 percent. ADRs of Woodside Petroleum Ltd., Australia’s
second-biggest oil and gas producer, gained 0.8 percent in
Sydney after  oil prices  climbed.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average expiring in
June closed at 9,590 in Chicago on April 15, compared with 9,560
in Osaka, Japan. They were bid in the pre-market at 9,580 in
Osaka at 8:05 a.m. local time. Futures on  Australia ’s S&P/ASX
200 Index rose 0.3 percent today.  “The improvement in the U.S. data and higher commodity
prices mean investors will probably buy exporters and other
economically sensitive stocks,” said Ryuta Otsuka, a strategist
at Toyo Securities Co. in Tokyo.  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index rose 1.1 percent
today. In New York, the index gained 0.4 percent on April 15
after an index of consumer sentiment improved more than expected
and a gauge of manufacturing gained the most in a year.  The Thomson Reuters/University of Michigan preliminary
index of consumer sentiment rose to 69.6 on April 15, beating a
forecast by economists surveyed by Bloomberg News for the figure
to rise to 68.8.  Crude oil for May delivery climbed $1.55 to settle at
$109.66 a barrel in  New York  on April 15, rising for a third
day. The London Metal Exchange Index of six metals advanced the
most in a week.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index lost 1.4 percent this year
through April 15, compared with gains of 4.9 percent by the  S&P
500  and 0.7 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the
Asian benchmark are valued at 13.1 times estimated earnings on
average, compared with 13.5 times for the S&P 500 and 11.2 times
for the Stoxx 600.  To contact the reporters on this story:
